But note how for all those non-binary cases, every single implementation ends up using something different; binary is the common language.
E.g. most SSD's are multi-level cells, and for fiber optics and HD's the encoding schemes are such that talking about bits makes no sense.
Actually neither data storage nor transmission use binary these days; the non-competitiveness is for logic circuits, where binary rules.
Indeed - the only reason ternary didn't win over binary is no-one figured out how to make ternary hardware as good as binary hardware.
